  "response_text": "The water cycle, also known as the hydrological cycle, is a continuous process by which water circulates between the Earth's oceans, atmosphere, and land. It involves several key stages: evaporation, condensation, precipitation, infiltration, and runoff. Here\u2019s a detailed explanation with my confidence ratings for each stage:\n\n1. **Evaporation**: Water from oceans, rivers, lakes, and other bodies of water heats up by the sun and turns into vapor. Plants also release water vapor into the air through a process called transpiration. This stage is well understood and documented, so I would rate my confidence at 9.\n\n2. **Condensation**: As water vapor rises and cools in the atmosphere, it turns back into liquid droplets, forming clouds. This process is also well-studied and has a high degree of certainty, so I would rate my confidence at 8.\n\n3. **Precipitation**: When these droplets combine and grow heavy, they fall from clouds",
